<HEADLINE>
NEW SPORTS MINISTER TO CONTINUE PREDECESSOR'S 'GOLDEN PROJECT'
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  Jan.  31 (CNA) 01/31/07  12:56:35 (By Elizabeth Hsu)
</P>
<P>
New National Council on Physical Fitness and Sports (NCPFS)
Minister Yang Chung- ho said Wednesday he will continue his
predecessor's "Golden Project" aimed at cultivating and training
elite athletes.
</P>
<P>
Yang made the comments after receiving the official seal of
office from the outgoing minister, Chen Chuan-show, in a
changeover ceremony held at the NCPFS headquarters. The ceremony
was witnessed by Minister without Portfolio Wu Feng- shan.
</P>
<P>
The new sports minister said he believes an administrator must
not be short- sighted and profit-oriented, especially in efforts
to cultivate athletes who will represent the country in
international sports events and strive to break world records.
</P>
<P>
"Substainable management is the only way, " the former president
of Taipei Physical Education College (TPEC) said.
</P>
<P>
Also attending the changeover ceremony were Chinese Taipei
Olympic Committee Vice Chairman Tsai Si-chue, as well as other
sports officials and representatives.
</P>
<P>
Yang, who graduated from the old Taipei Municipal Junior College
of Physical Education which in 1996 was transformed into TPEC,
holds a doctoral degree in education from the University of South
Dakota in the United States.
</P>
